Here we show that the intermediate filament protein [TF] suppresses [TG] function through direct interaction with c-Fos, and that both proteins can interact and colocalize at the nuclear envelope (NE) in mammalian cells.

While much is known about the signaling pathways and physical interactions between NFAT and [TF] dimers following lymphocyte activation, few studies have addressed the role of [TG] composition in modulating NFAT:AP-1-dependent transcription.
